          "ADD-RES": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": [
                "THEO",
                "COMP"
              ],
              "free_text": [
                " Theoretical angular   distributions  have",
                " been calculated on the basis of the resonance theory",
                " of the compound nucleus."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "CORRECTION": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "The background  was  subtracted  but  had  negligible",
                " effect on the distribution."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "COMMENT": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": null,
              "free_text": [
                "Distinct peaks in the neutron spectrum at  1.3,  3.1,",
                " 7.4, and possibly at 1.7, 5.5, 9.2, and 10.5 MeV are",
                " observed.  The peaks at  1.3  and  3.1  MeV  can  be",
                " accounted for in terms of single-particle excitation",
                " modes  (2s1/2->2p3/2,1/2)  of  a   valence   neutron",
                " without  disturbing the O-16 core.  These correspond",
                " to 1-levels in  O-16  at  10.3  and  12.2  MeV  with",
                " transitions  leaving  O-17 in the 1/2+ excited state",
                " at 0.871 MeV.",
                "The angular    distribution   of   the   neutron   is",
                " predominantly  sin**2  at  low  energies.  At   high",
                " energies,  there  is an interference effects between",
                " electric dipole and quadrupole absorption."
              ]
            }
          ],
